UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Thursday to Sunday, 9:00 a.m. m.–3:00 p.m. m. (last entry around 2:00 p.m.).', tarifa_en = 'Adults (13+) $17,000; children (2–12) $15,000; combo with the Zoo $40,000 / $30,000. Tickets at the Zoo ticket offices or at TuBoleta.', descripcion_en = 'In the middle basin of the Cali River, a stone''s throw from the Zoo, one of the last relics of the tropical dry forest survives—one of the most threatened ecosystems on the planet—turned into a garden. The project was born in 2001 from the efforts of biologist Jorge Enrique Orejuela and other people and institutions that set out to recover the river basin; The energy company EPSA gave on loan the hectares where samanes, guayacans and orchids grow today, one hundred species of butterflies flutter and more than one hundred birds nest. 

Since 2017, the Cali Zoological Foundation renovated it with a master plan that includes a four-story viewpoint designed by architect Simón Vélez, from where the forest canopy and the mountain range can be seen. It is a biodiversity refuge and outdoor classroom at the same time.', datos_historicos_en = 'Promoted by the Cali Zoological Foundation to expand plant conservation. Reopened to the public in September 2024; managed by the Cali Zoo Foundation.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It is home to more than 190 species of plants, a hundred butterflies and about 120 species of birds.', 'Its viewpoint-tower was designed by Simón Vélez, world master of guadua architecture.', 'The forest it protects helps regulate the basin from which Cali takes much of its water.']::text[] WHERE id = 's18';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'According to programming; The exhibition halls and a good part of the concerts are free access, during institutional hours (Monday to Friday).', tarifa_en = 'Tuition-based academic programs; many exhibitions and concerts with free admission.', descripcion_en = 'Bellas Artes is the silent factory behind much of Cali''s cultural scene: the first institution dedicated to the professional teaching of art in southwestern Colombia. It was born in the early 1930s at the initiative of maestro Antonio María Valencia – Cali pianist and composer – as a Music Conservatory, and from there it grew to embrace music, the plastic arts, design and the performing arts. 

Generations of musicians, painters, designers and actors who today represent the city have passed through its classrooms, and milestones such as the Cali International Art Festival have emerged from its midst. A heritage institution and engine of renewal at the same time, it is one of those places that are not seen on the tourist agenda but support, from below, everything else.', datos_historicos_en = 'Founded in the early 1930s (Cali Conservatory of Music, 1932–1933) on the initiative of maestro Antonio María Valencia. In 1936 it was departmentalized as the Cali Conservatory–Departmental School of Fine Arts.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['The Cali International Art Festival arose from an idea by Fanny Mickey in the then "Palacio de Bellas Artes".', 'Its music conservatory is named after its founder, Antonio María Valencia.']::text[] WHERE id = 's32';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Tuesday to Sunday and holidays, 9:30 a.m. m.–4:30 p.m. m. (closed on the Tuesday following a holiday Monday).', tarifa_en = 'Adults $18,000; children $10,500; older adults and PwD $9,000; foreigners 10 USD (sale only at the box office).', descripcion_en = 'At the foot of the Central Mountain Range, in El Cerrito, this 19th century white house is a literary pilgrimage: here Jorge Isaacs set María, the crowning novel of Latin American romanticism, translated into more than thirty languages. The house—the “Sierra House” of the book—preserves the layout described in the novel: Efraín''s room with its vase of always fresh roses, María''s room, the study, the room where the family gathered to embroider and sing. 

Surrounded by water channels that prevented the passage of insects, with cool balconies, a rose garden and a view of the sugarcane plains and the giant samanes, the hacienda makes literature and territory merge. In front of it is the stone where, according to the novel, lovers sat, today witness of visitors who swear eternal love.', datos_historicos_en = 'Built between 1816 and 1828. It was acquired by Jorge Isaacs'' father in 1854. House museum administered by INCIVA; BIC of the Nation.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['Maria was published in 1867; In 2017 its 150 years were commemorated with the Jorge Isaacs Year.', 'In Efraín''s room, fresh roses are renewed every day, in memory of the ones María brought him.', 'Jorge Isaacs was the face of the old 50,000 Colombian peso bill.']::text[] WHERE id = 's36';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Monday to Friday, 9:00 a.m. m.–12:30 p.m. m. and 2:00–5:00 p.m. m.', tarifa_en = 'Free visit to the workshop-store (posters and products are sold separately).', descripcion_en = 'Squeezed between the colorful houses of San Antonio is a printing press that refuses to die. The Lantern has been operating since 1934, printing street posters with movable type and linoleum engraving—the same technique with which Gutenberg changed the world half a millennium ago—on machines that are living relics: a Marinoni press from Paris (1870), a Reliance from New York (1890), a Rápida di Lusso from Turin (1934). For decades his posters covered the walls of Cali announcing concerts, plays and political campaigns. 

Andrés Caicedo was a client and friend of the workshop. In 2016 it almost closed. But in 2017 a group of managers and graphic artists reactivated it, articulating the centuries-old craft with contemporary design, and today it is a living cultural company, gallery and emblem of popular Cali graphics, with exhibitions in Mexico, Italy, France and Germany.', datos_historicos_en = 'Founded in 1934. It was saved from bankruptcy in 2017 thanks to the union of its veteran workers and young designers. It has been operating since 1934; in San Antonio since 1987.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['Editorial Planeta chose her to illustrate the covers of the reissues of Andrés Caicedo, a historical client of the workshop.', 'His machines are relics: a Marinoni press from Paris from 1870, a Reliance from New York from 1890, and a Rápida di Lusso from Turin from 1934.', 'His posters have already gone around the world in exhibitions in Europe and America.']::text[] WHERE id = 's43';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Monday to Friday, 8:00 a.m. m.–6:00 p.m. m.; Saturdays, 3:00–6:00 p.m. m.; Sundays, 10:00 a.m. m.–6:00 p.m. m.', tarifa_en = 'Entry $20,000 (as a donation for its support).', descripcion_en = 'It all started with two projectors rescued from the trash—the same ones that had been used at the inauguration of the Jorge Isaacs Theater. From that wonderful coincidence, as its founder calls it, Caliwood was born, the first museum of cinematography in Colombia. Hugo Suárez Fiat, a lawyer and collector from Cali, gathered cameras, projectors, magic lanterns and posters that reconstruct the evolution of cinema and photography, from daguerreotypes of 1840 to projectors of the early 20th century. 

The name says it all: Caliwood is the nod to the irreverent cinema movement that Cali gave to the country in the seventies and eighties, with Luis Ospina, Carlos Mayolo and Andrés Caicedo at the helm. Walking through it is entering a time capsule of the seventh art, and a stubborn commitment to preserve the film memory of the city considered the mecca of Colombian cinema.', datos_historicos_en = 'Founded in 2008 by Hugo Suárez, a passionate collector. Founded on October 22, 2008 by Hugo Suárez Fiat.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It keeps 30 original still photos from the filming of María (1922), the first Colombian film.', 'It was the first museum institution in the country to offer audio guides via QR codes.', 'His collection started with two projectors used at the inauguration of the Jorge Isaacs Theater.']::text[] WHERE id = 's34';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Public square, open.', tarifa_en = 'Free.', descripcion_en = 'Cali''s kilometer zero. This square, surrounded by towering ''Roystonea regia'' palm trees, is the historic civic and commercial heart of the city. Around it stand emblematic buildings of republican and neoclassical architecture such as the Cathedral of San Pedro, the National Palace and the Otero Building. It is a vibrant place, full of red wine sellers, shoe shiners and passersby, where the daily pulse of the city is felt and all the stories intersect. The old colonial Plaza Mayor (later Plaza de la Constitución) was renamed Plaza de Caycedo in 1813, in honor of the hero Joaquín de Caycedo y Cuero; the central monument was erected in 1913.', datos_historicos_en = 'The former colonial Plaza Mayor was renamed Plaza de Cayzedo in 1913 in honor of the hero Joaquín de Cayzedo y Cuero, whose statue was erected that same year. It functioned as a public market until the end of the 19th century and was remodeled in 1986, to mark the 450th anniversary of the city.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['His royal palms are an inseparable part of his image.', 'It is surrounded by the National Palace, the Otero Building and the Cathedral of San Pedro.', 'It occupies nearly 6,500 square meters in the heart of the center.']::text[] WHERE id = 's39';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Climbing at dawn or in the morning is recommended (for safety and weather); It works as an ecopark (Bataclán).', tarifa_en = 'Free.', descripcion_en = 'The physical challenge par excellence of Cali people. Climbing the Three Crosses is a weekend morning ritual for thousands of people. The trail is steep and physically demanding, but the reward is an unbeatable view of the city and fresh orange juice at the top. The three large concrete crosses dominate the landscape and protect, according to legend, the city from the demon ''Buziraco''. According to tradition, a cross was erected on the hill to ''conjure'' the devil Buziraco; The three current crosses, in particular, date from the late 1930s.', datos_historicos_en = 'According to tradition, in 1837 Franciscan friars placed three guadua crosses to conjure the legend of "Buziraco." The concrete crosses that today crown the hill were erected around 1937-1938, after the previous ones fell in the 1925 earthquake.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['The central cross measures about 26 meters high.', 'Every May 3, Day of the Cross, and during Holy Week, pilgrimages are carried out.', 'It is one of the most popular sports climbs in the city.']::text[] WHERE id = 's65';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Open to the public; It is recommended to coordinate the visit or the tour (Siloé Route) directly with the museum (David Gómez / channel @siloécitytv).', tarifa_en = 'Free.', descripcion_en = 'In a house with a hand-painted facade in the El Cortijo neighborhood, commune 20, one of the most unique museums in Colombia operates: a place where silence is prohibited. The Popular Museum of Siloam is unlike any other. Here you can shout, touch objects, take photos, sing and leave your own mark. Its creators call it a "countermuseum": a political and aesthetic commitment that gives back to the neighborhood the power to tell its own story, against the logic of the traditional museum—silent, with untouchable showcases and curated by experts. It was founded in August 2000 by David Gómez, community leader, volunteer guide and empirical historian born and raised on the hillside, and is supported by the community itself: the pieces are donated by neighbors and the curation is born from dialogue, memory and even conflict. 

It is the house of David, and it is also all of Siloam. Shoes hanging from the ceiling, a burned bicycle in the entrance, violins on the wall, photos from the 50s, masks, helmets, a piece of coal, devil costumes. All apparent chaos is ordered when David narrates: each object has a story, and that story is the memory of the territory. The museum understands that the neighborhood itself is the museum, and that is why its team has offered since 1998 the Tourist Route through Siloé and the "memory walks" through the steep streets, steps and alleys of the commune. They practice what they call "living museology": giving a voice to those who were historically silenced.', datos_historicos_en = 'The museum narrates Siloé from its deepest roots: the Yanacona indigenous people, the enslaved Africans and the miners from Marmato (Caldas) who arrived attracted by coal —Siloé is literally built on pits. It has a room dedicated to the armed conflict and the memory of the M-19.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['The motto that greets the visitor: "It is forbidden to be silent. Att. The Memory of Siloé."', 'The only requirement for an object to enter the museum is that it tells something, that it is a memory of the territory.', 'The museum is articulated with the route of the hillside that includes the viewpoint of La Estrella de Siloé.']::text[] WHERE id = 's119';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Open; Bathing area in the river and trails (higher influx on weekends).', tarifa_en = 'Free entry (some services and private parking spaces apart).', descripcion_en = 'If you want to know what a real Caleño does on Sunday, go to Pance. This river with cold, crystalline waters that flows directly from the Farallones is the natural and democratic spa of the city. The ecopark offers walking trails, picnic areas, lakes and direct access to the river. It is a sacred ritual to immerse yourself in its waters to ''get off the heat'' and then enjoy a wood-fired chicken stew in the surrounding restaurants. The Pance River rises in the Farallones de Cali National Natural Park; Its riverbank was consolidated as a recreation area and ecopark of the city.', datos_historicos_en = 'The Government of the Valley acquired the properties around 1970 to create the Popular and Recreational Spa of the Pance River. Since 1985 it has been administered by the Corporation for Popular Recreation, which consolidated the "Health Park".', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['The Pance River rises in the Farallones de Cali National Natural Park, at about 4,000 m above sea level. n. m.', 'On sunny weekends it can receive tens of thousands of visitors.', 'Its name comes from the Pance indigenous people, former inhabitants of the area.']::text[] WHERE id = 's20';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Monday through Saturday, guided tours at 11:00 a.m. m., 2:30 p.m. m. and 5:00 p.m. m.; Sundays at 3:00 p.m. m. (closed holidays).', tarifa_en = '$16,000 per person (cultural contribution).', descripcion_en = 'On a block of the traditional Obrero neighborhood—the cradle of Cali salsa—there is a house that keeps the sonorous memory of an entire city. It all started in 1968, when photographer Carlos Alfredo Molina, camera in hand, began to photograph fair nights and the great artists who passed through Cali. From that curious lens was born an archive of more than 40,000 photographs that today is, by all accounts, the oldest salsa museum in the world. 

There are no cold showcases here: there is a track covered in black and white, walls covered with faces—Marvin Santiago, Gilberto Santa Rosa, Sonora Ponceña—and three generations of the same family who inherited the trade like someone who inherits a last name. More than a collection, it is a living testimony that in Cali culture is not only heard: it is inherited.', datos_historicos_en = 'Founded more than 50 years ago as a personal archive that was opened to the world. Founded in 1968 by Carlos Alfredo Molina; the oldest salsa museum in the world, with 40,000+ photographs.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It houses more than 40,000 photographs of musicians, orchestras and dancers.', 'There are only a handful of museums like this in the world: the others are in New York and Puerto Rico, and this is the oldest.', 'It also offers dance classes and supports children and young people of the Obrero.']::text[] WHERE id = 's25';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Open on performance days; box office and online sales according to billboard.', tarifa_en = 'Ticket according to event.', descripcion_en = 'In front of the Ortiz Bridge, next to La Ermita and the Parque de los Poetas, the Jorge Isaacs Theater gives the historic center an elegance from another era. It was born from a misfortune and an ambition: where the Teatro Salón Moderno once stood—consumed by a fire in 1928—the businessman Hermann S. Bohmer built a new theater and named it in honor of Jorge Isaacs, the author of María. It was inaugurated on December 26, 1931. 

In French neoclassical style with nods to Italian romanticism, decorated with Ionic capitals, a stained glass window of the city''s coat of arms and the effigy of the poet, it boasts one of the best acoustics in the country. After decades of abandonment, it was declared a National Monument and restored, and today it is once again home to concerts, opera and great shows.', datos_historicos_en = 'It opened its doors in 1931. It was closed and in ruins for years until its glorious restoration in the 80s, saving it from demolition. Room with 1,136 seats in four locations.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['A fire in its early years led to the creation of the Cali volunteer fire department.', 'Its acoustic box is one of the largest in Latin America.', 'Its name honors the author of María, Colombia''s most famous romantic novel.']::text[] WHERE id = 's22';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Monday to Friday 9:00 a.m. m.–7:00 p.m. m.; Saturdays 9:00 a.m. m.–6:00 p.m. m.; Sundays 10:00 a.m. m.–3:00 p.m. m.', tarifa_en = 'Free (all basic services).', descripcion_en = 'More than a book depository, the Departmental is a cultural plaza: the first departmental library in Colombia, born from a gesture of filial love. When the industrialist Jorge Garcés Borrero died in 1949, he left more than seven thousand books; His son Diego Garcés Giraldo, being governor of the Valley, donated them to found a public library in 1953 that would bear his father''s name. Convinced that "the progress of a society is made through education", he promoted it obsessively. 

After several offices, since 1990 it has occupied a 15,000 m² building next to Roosevelt Avenue, today the heart of the "Manzana del Saber". There are reading rooms with exhibitions, cinema, concerts, a valuable newspaper library and festivals such as "Hey, Look, Read". It embodies the idea that public culture has to be free and open doors.', datos_historicos_en = 'Created in 1953 by decree of Governor Diego Garcés Giraldo and inaugurated on June 13, 1954, from the personal library of Jorge Garcés Borrero. Its current headquarters, measuring 15,000 m², was completed in 1990.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['He was born with the ~7,000 books from the Garcés family''s personal library.', 'Every September it hosts the International Literature Festival "Hey, Look, Read".', 'Its newspaper archive preserves newspapers and magazines of great regional historical value.']::text[] WHERE id = 's15';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Evenings, usually Thursday through Saturday (from 9:00–11:00 p.m.).', tarifa_en = 'Cover/consumption depending on the night.', descripcion_en = 'In 1993, a trio of salsa-loving friends opened a salsa club on Avenida 5 Norte that they called Zaperoco. Over the years it passed into the hands of the Levy Cote family, who turned it into a bastion where the old and the modern coexist, with vinyl, live orchestras and a vocation that goes beyond rumba: to be a platform for the new bands in the city. In its beginnings, groups such as Herencia de Timbiquí performed on its stage. 

Its hallmark is the "Descargas Zaperoco" Thursdays—created together with the writer and music lover Umberto Valverde, a loyal client of the house—, large gatherings of musicians with rotating directors where the salsa is felt in the body. It is one of those places where the Cali night shows its most authentic side.', datos_historicos_en = 'Founded in 1993, it has stood the test of time while maintaining its pure essence. Founded in 1993.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['His Thursday "Zaperoco Downloads" were born together with the writer Umberto Valverde.', 'Herencia de Timbiquí passed through its stage in its beginnings.', 'It keeps live salsa alive, increasingly rare in the city.']::text[] WHERE id = 's28';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Monday to Saturday, 8:00 a.m. m.–5:00 p.m. m.', tarifa_en = 'Free or low-cost community training programs.', descripcion_en = 'In Potrero Grande, in the heart of the Aguablanca District—one of the territories hardest hit by inequality and largely populated by families displaced from the Pacific by the armed conflict—the Tecnocentro turns culture and technology into concrete opportunity. It was born from the dream of Sister Alba Stella Barreto, from the Paz y Bien Foundation, who wanted a neutral space where children could meet without the fear of "invisible borders" to learn theater, dance, music, robotics, video editing, programming and plastic arts. 

The result of a public-private alliance (Alvaralice Foundation, Comfandi, the Mayor''s Office, the Icesi University, the Ministry of Culture), it opened its doors around 2013 and since then it has served thousands of children and young people a year. It has its own symphony orchestra, public library and a Computer Clubhouse. It is proof that Cali''s cultural offer is also built, strongly, in the east.', datos_historicos_en = 'Inaugurated in 2013 thanks to the public-private alliance led by the Alvaralice Foundation. Founded in 2011.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['His symphony orchestra was formed with the Batuta Foundation; several of his young people received scholarships at the Conservatory of Fine Arts.', 'His Computer Clubhouse was articulated with MIT in Boston.', 'Every year he presents the show "Pescadores de Sueños" at the Municipal Theater.']::text[] WHERE id = 's33';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Building for commercial and office use; It can be seen from the Plaza de Cayzedo (without an internal tourist visit).', tarifa_en = 'Not applicable (can be seen from the outside).', descripcion_en = 'In a corner of the Plaza de Cayzedo, in front of the founding heart of Cali, stands the Otero Building: an eclectic mass of French republican inspiration that forever changed the landscape of the center. His story begins with a European dream. Businessman Emiliano Otero, dazzled by the architecture he had seen on his travels, decided to bring to Cali a building on par with those he admired on the old continent. In 1916 he bought Colonel Ocampo''s house, had it demolished and commissioned the work to the firm Borrero y Ospina, which built it between 1922 and 1926. 

The Otero was the first building in Cali built with a reinforced concrete structure, leaving the walls the role of simple enclosure: a technical innovation that allowed more height, more lightness and more decorative freedom. With him the replacement of the old colonial architecture with European academic eclecticism and modern techniques practically began. Its façade mixes Renaissance and Baroque elements, and in the corner a dome with oculi crowns an octagonal volume that gives it verticality and breaks the symmetry.', datos_historicos_en = '1916: Emiliano Otero buys and demolishes Colonel Ocampo''s house. 1922–1926: construction by the firm Borrero y Ospina. During its first years it was the epicenter of Cali social life. July 25, 1977: declared a National Monument.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['Hollywood actor Tyrone Power stayed at the Europa Hotel in 1939.', 'The Borrero y Ospina firm consolidated itself, practically with this building, as the most important builders'' house in Cali.', 'The building also had a dark chapter: in 1984 it was the scene of the so-called "Diners Club massacre."']::text[] WHERE id = 's108';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Monday to Friday, 8:00 a.m. m.–12:00 m. and 2:00–5:30 p.m. m.', tarifa_en = 'Gratuitous.', descripcion_en = 'On the second floor of the Cali Cultural Center, the written memory of the city is kept, volume by volume. The Historical Archive of Cali is the entity in charge of guarding, organizing and disseminating the documentary heritage of the people of Cali, following the guidelines of the General Archive of the Nation. On its shelves lie nearly 9,000 volumes—about 800 linear meters—of documentation produced by the different government figures that the city has had: the colonial council, the municipality and today the district. It is one of the most important places to investigate the history of Cali, and also one of the best kept: its oldest document is a document from the Cabildo from 1564.', datos_historicos_en = 'It was created by Municipal Decree No. 378 of June 24, 1958. Since February 2000 it has been permanently located in the Cultural Center of the city. It organizes its collection into five documentary collections.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['Cali anticipated the Royal Decree of 1573 by ten years, which ordered the councils to keep Minute Books.', 'Among its documents are letters of freedom from enslaved people.', 'The oldest document in the Cali Archive is from 1564.']::text[] WHERE id = 's113';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Open to the public during worship hours (masses).', tarifa_en = 'Free admission.', descripcion_en = 'The neo-Gothic image of La Ermita, blue and white next to the river, is one of the most recognized postcards of Cali. But the church we see today is relatively young: the original hermitage, built at the beginning of the 17th century, was destroyed by the earthquake of June 7, 1925; Only the venerated image of the Lord of the Reed was saved from it. On these ruins, two Cali sisters - Micaela and Asunción Castro Borrero - promoted the construction of the current temple, inspired by the cathedral of Ulm, in Germany.\n\nCompleted in concrete and inaugurated in 1942, La Ermita is almost a catalog of the world brought to Cali: Carrara marble on its altars, bells cast in France, and a musical clock and stained glass windows with the twelve apostles commissioned in Amsterdam. A little piece of Europe on the riverbank, which survived where the city lost almost all of its ancient architecture.', datos_historicos_en = 'The current construction began in 1930 and was completed in 1942, replacing a 17th-century chapel. The current neo-Gothic temple was built in the first half of the 20th century (1930s–1940s), replacing the colonial hermitage ruined by earthquakes; Its style is inspired by European Gothic cathedrals.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It keeps the image of the ''Lord of the Cane'', the only survivor of the 1787 earthquake.', 'Its musical clock rings every hour, brightening the center.', 'It preserves the colonial image of the Lord of the Cane (or Lord of Miracles), survivor of the earthquakes.']::text[] WHERE id = 's16';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Open public space.', tarifa_en = 'Free.', descripcion_en = 'It is Cali''s modern ''reception room''. An extensive and airy pedestrian promenade on the banks of the river that transformed the city center. Here the afternoon breeze is the protagonist. It is the democratic place where people from Cali of all ages and social classes converge to walk, have a coffee, listen to spontaneous music or simply watch life go by. It connects the historical architecture of the Ortiz Bridge and the Hermitage with the modernity of the administrative center. Inaugurated in 2013, after pedestrianizing the old section of Colombia Avenue on the banks of the Cali River.', datos_historicos_en = 'Built starting in 2012 within the "Megaobras" program of the administration of Mayor Rodrigo Guerrero, it was inaugurated on May 16, 2013, on the longest urban tunnel in the country.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['The pedestrian promenade extends about 980 meters over the "World Cup Tunnel."', 'Between 6,000 and 7,000 people walk through it every day.', 'His "bridge of love" was filled with padlocks, in the style of the Pont des Arts in Paris.']::text[] WHERE id = 's3';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'open area; strong night movement.', tarifa_en = 'Free (consumptions apart).', descripcion_en = 'Residential neighborhood in the north of Cali, developed in the mid-20th century, which over time established itself as one of the main gastronomic and nightlife epicenters of the city.', datos_historicos_en = 'Traditional residential neighborhood in the north of Cali, emerged at the beginning of the 20th century, which over time consolidated itself as a gastronomic and nightlife epicenter.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It concentrates a good part of Cali''s haute cuisine restaurants.', 'It houses the contemporary art space Lugar a Dudas.', 'It is a common starting point for gastronomic tours of the city.']::text[] WHERE id = 's61';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'Open daily, with more atmosphere in the evening.', tarifa_en = 'Free entry (crafts and food are paid separately).', descripcion_en = 'The heart of crafts and bohemian culture in Cali. This craft park, architecturally built in tiers on a hill, is filled with booths where local artisans make and sell jewelry, leather work, wood, and musical instruments. But more than a market, it is a living cultural center: Thursdays are nights of oral storytelling (storytellers), and on weekends there are folk dances and live Andean music. A space of cultural resistance. It was consolidated as a park and craft market in the last decades of the 20th century; It is a reference point for the Cali artisan trade.', datos_historicos_en = 'The project began in 1987 at the initiative of Artesanías de Colombia (promoted by María Cristina Palau Londoño) and was officially inaugurated on July 12, 1990. In 1993 it passed to municipal administration.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It owes its name to the cross on the hill, shrouded in Cali legends from the 16th century.', 'It brings together around 120 artisan families on its four levels.', 'Its theater hosts films, stories and poetry recitals.']::text[] WHERE id = 's11';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'open area; strong gastronomic and nightlife.', tarifa_en = 'Free (consumptions apart).', descripcion_en = 'One of the traditional neighborhoods of Cali, on the banks of the Cali River, adjacent to San Antonio and the La Tertulia Museum; Over the years it became established as a bohemian, gastronomic and antiques area. In its surroundings (Bulevar del Río) antique and flea markets are held on weekends.', datos_historicos_en = 'The El Peñón neighborhood was developed at the beginning of the 20th century as an upper-class residential area.', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['It houses a statue of Benito Juárez donated by Mexico.', 'It is known for its large trees that provide cool shade all day.']::text[] WHERE id = 's60';
UPDATE sites SET horario_en = 'According to event programming.', tarifa_en = 'Ticket according to event.', descripcion_en = 'Where the pink zone begins on Sixth Avenue stands the Calima Theater, a chest of art loaded with history. Inaugurated on November 27, 1963 —with the film *A Night in Hong Kong*, within the 1st Japanese Film Festival—, it was one of the largest and most beloved movie theaters in Cali. Its name evokes the Calima indigenous people; Its Roman-style architecture arranges the stands in the shape of an amphitheater under a high nave, with capacity for about 1,265 spectators and good visibility from any chair. It is listed as an Asset of Cultural Interest and architectural heritage of the city.', datos_historicos_en = 'November 27, 1963: inauguration, under the direction of Galindo Buenaventura. 
70s: headquarters of decisive film clubs, including Andrés Caicedo''s Cali Film Club. 
July 9, 1999: last screening and closing. 
October 2016 – July 2017: complete restoration and reopening (with a work by the Bambazú group).', datos_curiosos_en = ARRAY['The restoration recovered original details such as the chairs, the fountain and the bronze doors at the entrance, according to the Special Heritage Protection Plan.', 'It has a special location for 20 people with reduced mobility, with a "caterpillar" imported from Italy to facilitate access.']::text[] WHERE id = 's41';
